Stars will begin the year with a distance learning program after Labor Day, offering Grab-n-Go packages each week with STEAM activities and snacks as well as academic enrichment.
Curbside pickup will also be available for virtual students. Packets will be sent home with onsite students each Tuesday after school, and curbside pickup will be available for virtual students at the back door of KMS from 3:30-4:00 each Tuesday. Stars programming will be reevaluated on Sept. 29 for a possible blended program. If you have any questions, please contact Lou Barrick at lbarrick @kingfisher.k12.ok.us or Terry Willis a twillis@kingfisher.k12.ok.us.
Sincerely,
Lou Barrick and Terry Willis

post_text:
With the help of the county health department, Kingfisher Public Schools would like to announce that we are able to bring the 3rd grade students back to school on Monday, Aug. 24. During our contact tracing period, no other positive cases were found besides what was initially reported.

Due to the majority of 4th grade teachers being quarantined, the 4th grade students will not be able to return until Tuesday, Sept. 1st.

Those in 3rd grade who tested positive or identified as close contacts of the positive individuals are still on the Distance Learning Plan until their quarantine date is over. As always, please screen your child(ren) each morning and keep them at home if they exhibit any symptoms listed in the COVID screening check-list.

Hello Parents,
We just received notice that a 2nd Heritage Elementary teacher has tested positive and a couple more who have been contact traced to them. We are in the process of notifying parents of specific classrooms at Heritage. The other sites are not experiencing this outbreak at this time. Heritage will transition to distance learning platform tomorrow morning for 14 days. All other sites will be on regular time. If you have a child at Heritage and children in other sites, please keep the siblings at home as well. We will be releasing more information as it becomes available.

Kingfisher Public School plans on starting back traditional school with the students on Aug. 12th. We understand the situation with Covid-19 is ever changing. Plans will be developed that address safety protocols and distance learning in the event that school is forced to close for a period of time.

To get things started, we have to get feedback from parents. This survey gives us a starting point so that we can begin to plan accordingly. Parent participation is vital in gathering the information we need in order to have a successful start to the school year. This survey will be open until Wednesday July 8th at 9:00 pm.

It is only necessary to complete the form one time per family. If you receive the survey more than one time please disregard the others.

Kingfisher Public Schools Survey -https://forms.gle/EEmw9LH7nimi1Bso9

Thank you for your time.

Kingfisher Public Schools

post_text:
The Kingfisher Educational Foundation made it possible for Heritage students to meet author Julia Cook on Monday, February 25th.
Julia Cook, former teacher and elementary school counselor, is the author of children‚Äôs books addressing life skills, friendships, safety, communication, behavior, as well as physical and mental health. Children relate to her unique talented writing style, ranging in topic from BOOGERS to BULLYING.
During each hour long presentation, Mrs. Julia Cook highlighted some of her award-winning books for third and fourth grade students. She addressed the topics of attitude, organization, rumors, personal safety, and responsibility while also explaining the writing and publishing process of becoming a published author.

post_text: PTO started a new tradition this year challenging 4th graders to submit artwork for the Carnival t-shirt design. The winner was Kadyn Daugherty, and her design will be printed on the front of white t-shirts. Orders are due to school by Friday, March 31st. Order forms are available at the office.
